======================================================================
PART 1: DEHN INVARIANT AND THE THREE RATIONAL ANGLES
======================================================================

Niven's theorem: rational angles with rational cosine
θ/π    cos(θ)
      0   1.000
    1/3   0.500
    1/2   0.000
    2/3  -0.500
      1  -1.000

Essential denominators of θ/π: {1, 2, 3, 4, 6}
Reduced form denominators: {1, 2, 3}
These are: {unit, KEY₁, KEY₂}!

Regular tetrahedron dihedral angle: arccos(1/3) = 0.3918265520π
  This is IRRATIONAL relative to π!
  So the Dehn invariant D(tetrahedron) ≠ 0
  Tetrahedron is NOT scissors-congruent to the cube

Platonic solid dihedral angles:
  Tetrahedron    : θ = 0.39182655π, cos(θ) = 0.33333333  
  Cube           : θ = 0.50000000π, cos(θ) = 0.00000000  rational!
  Octahedron     : θ = 0.60817345π, cos(θ) = -0.33333333  
  Dodecahedron   : θ = 0.64758362π, cos(θ) = -0.44721360  
  Icosahedron    : θ = 0.76772047π, cos(θ) = -0.74535599  

Only the CUBE has rational dihedral angle (π/2)!
cos(π/2) = 0 — the simplest rational value
Cube dihedral angle denominator: 2 = KEY₁

======================================================================
PART 2: ALTERNATING SUM AND SIMPLEX PACKING
======================================================================

I(-1) = χ(Ind(CG(T))) = Euler characteristic of independence complex

The independence complex Ind(G) of a graph G:
  Vertices: vertices of G
  k-simplices: independent sets of size k+1
  χ = Σ (-1)^k f_k where f_k = number of k-simplices

I(-1) ≤ 1 means the independence complex has χ ≤ 1
This constrains the topology: no 'extra' holes or components

ANALOGY: Dehn invariant ↔ I(-1)
  Dehn invariant = obstruction to scissors congruence
  I(-1) - 1 = obstruction to 'tournament simplicity'
  Both vanish when the structure is 'maximally symmetric'

THE KEY₁ CONNECTION:
  Cube: dihedral angle = π/KEY₁, Dehn = 0
  'Simple' tournaments: I(KEY₁) mod KEY₁ = 1 (Rédei)
  Both: KEY₁ = 2 governs the vanishing condition

======================================================================
PART 3: THE BIFURCATION SEQUENCE
======================================================================

BIFURCATION HYPOTHESIS:
At n = p² (p odd prime), the I(-1) distribution changes character

Edges and tournament counts at bifurcation points:
  n= 3: C(3,2)=  3 edges, 2^3 = 8.000e+00 labeled tournaments
  n= 5: C(5,2)= 10 edges, 2^10 = 1.024e+03 labeled tournaments
  n= 7: C(7,2)= 21 edges, 2^21 = 2.097e+06 labeled tournaments
  n= 9: C(9,2)= 36 edges, 2^36 = 6.872e+10 labeled tournaments
  n=11: C(11,2)= 55 edges, 2^55 = 3.603e+16 labeled tournaments
  n=13: C(13,2)= 78 edges, 2^78 = 3.022e+23 labeled tournaments
  n=25: C(25,2)=300 edges, 2^300 = 2.037e+90 labeled tournaments

Why n=9 is special:
  9 = KEY₂² = 3²
  9 = h(E₇)/det(E₇) = CS boundary
  9 = h∨(F₄) = dual Coxeter number
  9 = rank(E₈) + 1 (the 'next' vertex beyond E₈)
  C(9,2) = 36 = 6² = (KEY₁·KEY₂)²
  36 = 4·9 = KEY₁²·KEY₂²

k-nacci roots near the bifurcation points:
  r_ 2 = 1.618033988749895, 2-r_2 = 3.82e-01
  r_ 3 = 1.839286755214161, 2-r_3 = 1.61e-01
  r_ 4 = 1.927561975482925, 2-r_4 = 7.24e-02
  r_ 5 = 1.965948236645485, 2-r_5 = 3.41e-02
  r_ 7 = 1.991964196605035, 2-r_7 = 8.04e-03
  r_ 9 = 1.998029470262287, 2-r_9 = 1.97e-03
  r_11 = 1.999510401978285, 2-r_11 = 4.90e-04
  r_25 = 1.000000000000000, 2-r_25 = 1.00e+00
  r_49 = 1.000000000000000, 2-r_49 = 1.00e+00

Weighted k-nacci roots (weight=2) near bifurcation:
  s_ 2 = 2.732050807568878, 3-s_2 = 2.68e-01
  s_ 3 = 2.919639565839419, 3-s_3 = 8.04e-02
  s_ 4 = 2.974449244552462, 3-s_4 = 2.56e-02
